Limit range and resource quota, namespace governance.

Once you have more than one team sharing a cluster, you do not want a best effort pod with no limits hogging a whole node, or a careless test accidentally requesting a hundred see-pee-you cores. Two cluster admin objects govern that, both namespace scoped.

The first is a limit range. It does two things. It supplies defaults, so when a pod is created without requests or limits, the ay-pee-eye server fills them in from the limit range. And it sets caps, rejecting pods whose values fall outside an allowed minimum and maximum. So after applying a limit range to a namespace, every container created there without limits gets sensible defaults, and anything asking for more than the maximum is rejected at creation time.

The second is a resource quota. Where a limit range governs each individual object, a resource quota caps the sum across the whole namespace. The total requested see-pee-you, the total memory, the total limits, and even the counts of objects, like how many pods or services the namespace may contain.

There is an important interaction between the two. If a resource quota in a namespace caps total requests or limits, then every pod must declare those values, otherwise the quota cannot account for it. That is exactly where a limit range earns its keep, by supplying defaults so that ordinary pods satisfy the quota without every author having to spell out resources by hand.

Together they are how a platform team turns a shared cluster into fair, bounded slices, one namespace per team, each with its own budget and its own sensible defaults.
